    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix incorrect pdu_index handling in NPDCCH unpacking function\n\n### Summary\nThe `unpack_dl_config_npdcch_pdu_rel13_value()` function in the NFAPi P7 codec was incorrectly casting the `pdu_index` field from `uint16_t*` when the structure actually defines it as `int16_t`. This caused negative pdu_index values to be interpreted incorrectly, leading to unexpected behavior in the OAI5G stack.\n\nThis fix corrects the type casting to match the structure definition and ensures consistent handling across all related packing/unpacking functions.\n\n### Changes\n- `nfapi/open-nFAPI/nfapi/src/nfapi_p7.c`: Fixed casting of `pdu_index` field in `unpack_dl_config_npdcch_pdu_rel13_value()` function from `(uint16_t*)` to `(int16_t*)`\n- `nfapi/open-nFAPI/nfapi/src/nfapi_p7.c`: Applied consistent fixes to related functions for `nbch` and `ndlsch` PDU types\n- `nfapi/open-nFAPI/nfapi/src/nfapi_p7.c`: Updated packing functions to properly cast `int16_t` values to `uint16_t` during serialization\n\n### Reproduction\nTo reproduce the issue:\n1. Configure OAI5G gNB with NPDCCH PDU configuration using negative pdu_index values\n2. Observe incorrect pdu_index values being processed in the downlink configuration\n3. Monitor for unexpected behavior in PDU handling, particularly with negative index values\n4. The issue manifests as incorrect PDU scheduling and potential misalignment between expected and actual PDU processing\n\nThe fix ensures that negative pdu_index values are correctly interpreted according to the specification, resolving the unexpected behavior in the 5G stack.\n"
}